Introduction ¶

Dataset Source

The dataset used in this report was sourced from Kaggle at https://www.kaggle.com/rajeevw/ufcdata (Warrier, 2019). The dataset includes all events from the dawn of the Ultimate Fighting Championship (UFC) in 1993 to 21 March 2021.

Dataset Details

Each row in the dataset represents a fight and contains both fighters' statistics leading up to the match. Fighters are labeled red and blue. Each fighter's statistics include average damage, inflicted and received (denoted by the prefix 'opp'), in all of his previous fights; detailed fight records including winning and losing streaks; and such biometrics as height, reach and age. The overall structure of the dataset as it stands now is most appropriate for predictive modeling, but ill-fitted for plotting for insights. Hence we will modify the dataset to plot more meaningful plots.

The raw dataset has a total of 144 columns and 6013 rows. We shall reduce the number of features and drop observations with missing values in the upcoming phase of data cleaning and pre-processing.

Dataset Variables

The features in the dataset are set out in the table below. All features with avg in their names store compiled data up to the current fight, which corresponds to each row. For example, 'B_avg_SIG_STR_pct' of a particular observation has the mean of the blue fighter's significant strikes out of total strikes (in fraction) in all of his/her fights prior to the current fight. For all this type of features, there are _opp_ counterparts. From 'B_avg_opp_SIG_STR_pct' column, we can find out the same information against the blue fighter by all the fighters he/she has previously faced. The _opp_ counterparts are intentionally excluded from the table below for conciseness. Since each observation contains two fighters' statistics, assume that for every feature of B_fighter, there is an equivalent of R_fighter, which is not also included in the table below for word economy.

Only some of the features will be utilised in Phase 1 while others will be used in Phase 2. With this in mind, let us explore the dataset features.

Side Notes

Significant strikes are defined as all strikes at distance and power strikes in the clinch and on the ground. (DraftKings, n.d.)

Response Variable ¶

When it comes to sports, predicting the winner is generally of most interest among regular viewers, ardent sports fans and sports data analysts. However, since our target feature should be numerical, not categorical, we have decided to create a derived feature R_post_fight_win_streak from existing R_current_win_streak and Winner.

R_current_win_streak does not accurately reflect the winning streak in all the previous fights before the current fight, but it holds the same value as R_longest_win_streak. First, we will rectify the values of the former feature. Next, the result of the current fight, represented in Winner, will be factored in so that the target feature is set to 0 or R_current_win_streak $+$ 1, depending on the outcome of a fight.

Goals and Objectives ¶

As the abbreviation MMA (Mixed Martial Arts) denotes, fighting has mostly been considered more of arts than science. This perception was turned on its head after the advent of Royce Gracie at UFC 1. He had brought in an algorithmic system of fighting style and established himself as a champion until other fighters caught up to his fight algorithms, namely Brazilian Jiu-jitsu. Since then, a great many of good fighters have taken a 'if-else/while' algorithmic approach, rendering data on fights ripe for machine learning analytics. A lot is at stake when fighters enter the octagon. One brutal fight can be the harbinger of the end of a fighter's career.

There is enough initiative to ascertain what attributes highly correlate with fighters on a winning streak. During the data exploration and visualisation in Phase 1, we will try to gain insight into existing correlations between attributes (descriptive features) and winners. First, we will look at the number of fights across weight divisions to get a general idea of fight distributions. The attributes associated with winners can be categorized as fixed and improvable; As an analysis of a fixed attribute, we aim to find out how many winners have a longer reach than opponents. We could then analyze the relationship between the winning fighter's stance, somewhat fixed yet improvable through training, and the number of his/her consecutive wins. We will also examine data on improvable attributes among winning fighters; Improvable factors include striking, wrestling, submission, etc.

The ultimate objective of this project is to predict the number of consecutive wins post-fight based on cumulative data available prior to the fight. We aim to produce a model with a high R$^2_{adj}$ so that we gain deeper insight into what attributes most correlate with winning streaks. If it proves futile to improve the model fit of our multiple regression, we shall endeavour to predict the values of our response feature with the help of Neural Networks (NN) models.

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing ¶

Overview¶

In this section, we will take prerequisite steps to cleaning our data for predictive modelling. The preprocessing steps are as follows:

  1. Check whether there is any oddity in the values of features.

  2. Change names of columns and values as required

  3. Address irrelevant features.

  4. Check for rows with missing or unusual values and drop them.

  5. Create another version of df without single outliers.

In [9]:
# Make sure there's no space surroudning the names
df['R_fighter'] = df['R_fighter'].str.strip()
df['B_fighter'] = df['B_fighter'].str.strip()

r_fighters = pd.Index(df['R_fighter'])
b_fighters = pd.Index(df['B_fighter'])

fighters = list(r_fighters | b_fighters)

# Dictionary to hold fighters' names ,winning streaks and draws
win_streaks = {fighter: 0 for fighter in fighters}
lose_streaks = {fighter: 0 for fighter in fighters}
draws = {fighter: 0 for fighter in fighters}

# Traverse from the past to the present
df = df.iloc[::-1]
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    # Update _draw, _current_win_streak and _current_lose_streak so that their values are based on the fight records prior to the current fight
    df.at[index, 'B_draw'] = draws[row['B_fighter']]
    df.at[index, 'R_draw'] = draws[row['R_fighter']]
    df.at[index, 'B_current_win_streak'] = win_streaks[row['B_fighter']]
    df.at[index, 'R_current_win_streak'] = win_streaks[row['R_fighter']]
    df.at[index, 'B_current_lose_streak'] = lose_streaks[row['B_fighter']]
    df.at[index, 'R_current_lose_streak'] = lose_streaks[row['R_fighter']]
    
    if row['Winner'] == 'Red':
        win_streaks[row['R_fighter']] += 1
        win_streaks[row['B_fighter']] = 0 
        lose_streaks[row['B_fighter']] += 1
        lose_streaks[row['R_fighter']] = 0
    elif row['Winner'] == 'Blue':
        win_streaks[row['B_fighter']] += 1
        win_streaks[row['R_fighter']] = 0
        lose_streaks[row['R_fighter']] += 1
        lose_streaks[row['B_fighter']] = 0
    else: # Draw
        win_streaks[row['R_fighter']] = 0
        win_streaks[row['B_fighter']] = 0 
        lose_streaks[row['B_fighter']] = 0
        lose_streaks[row['R_fighter']] = 0
        # If this fight ends up in a draw, store the result in draws
        draws[row['B_fighter']] += 1
        draws[row['R_fighter']] += 1
        
    df.at[index, 'R_post_fight_win_streak'] = win_streaks[row['R_fighter']]    
    df.at[index, 'B_post_fight_win_streak'] = win_streaks[row['B_fighter']]
    df.at[index, 'R_post_fight_lose_streak'] = lose_streaks[row['R_fighter']]    
    df.at[index, 'B_post_fight_lose_streak'] = lose_streaks[row['B_fighter']]    

# Set df in the original order
df = df.iloc[::-1]

According to the statistics summaries above, _total_time_fought_seconds's maximum value goes only up to 1500 seconds, which equals five 5-minute rounds. Worse yet, its definition from the source is ambiguous. The most likely interpretation is that this column is concerned with the current fight's result. As we are only interested in the cumulative data prior to the current fight, we shall drop the columns, for _total_rounds_fought can be substituted as a measure for longevity of a fighter's career.

In keeping with the best practice, we will move the target feature r_post_fight_win_streak to the end of the columns.

Data Exploration and Visualisation

Univariate Visualisation¶

Histogram Across Weight Divisions¶

We first get the lay of the land with respect to how proportionally fights are distributed across the weight classes. We see below that the male division as a whole takes on the bell curve of a normal distribution, most likely influenced by the weight distribution of the general male population. We can statistically say male fighters in the lightweight and welterweight divisions have to go through more fights on average to earn themselves championship fights. We also learn the female division is not representative of the general female population, indicating only women of certain body types compete, which is consistent with the fact that women cannot move up weight classes as freely as men.

Three-Variable Visualisation¶

Barplot of Average Headshots Landed on Losing Fighters by Opponents Juxtaposed with Age and Weight Class¶

We now select fighters on a losing streak for 2 or more consecutive fights and see what jumps out in the visualized data. Prior to their most recently defeated fight, they have taken an average of 25 shot to the head per fight. In contrast to these fighters, fighters on a winning streak take 16 shots to the head on average per fight.

Women's weight divisions have more marked variability in the average number of landed headshots, indicating greater variability in technique compared to the men's.

We also see that regardless of whether fighters have been winning or losing, the older they are, the more shots to the head on average they receive, more often than not.

Summary and Conclusion ¶

Our raw dataset was by no means perfect as it came with a few logical slips that needed correction, after which we were confident in the integrity of our derived response feature R_post_fight_win_streak. We have dropped the features whose values definitely do not contribute to the better fit of our predictive model. For Phase 2, we have renamed the columns as required and created another version of the dataset that contains no outliers.

Through visualisation of our dataset, we now understand a merit of weight cutting, especially for those whose walking around weights indicate they belong to the lightweight division, but they trim down a great deal to the featherweight to gain a weight advantage. As fight counts in each division are indicative of its total population, there is a higher probability that the lightweight and welterweight divisions will house a larger number of highly technical fighters. For that reason, lightweight fighters who think like statisticians might want to consider competing at the featherweight class. However, those who weigh between the welterweight and middleweight divisions may want to skimp on weight-cutting and try the heavier division should they have an unsuccessful run in the lighter division.

We intuitively understand fighters with a longer reach are at an advantage. Data have shown slightly higher win counts for slightly lengthier fighters. However, the difference in counts gets rather significant when there is 10 centimeters or more difference in the reach.

We take for granted more weapons will serve well fighters in their pursuit of winning. Hence fighters today display spectacular kicks as part of their weaponry. One of the key factors determining who wins is the number of significant strikes. Data show that fighters who win a match without leg-kick attempts still land as many significant strikes as those with 10 or more leg-kick attempts.

Fighters on a losing streak are characterized by a cumulative average of 20 or more shots to the head in all their previous fights. In comparison to them, fighters on a winning streak tend to absorb fewer headshots. Fighters might benefit from practicing parrying, ducking and sliding away punches aimed at their heads followed by their own share of punches to the opponent's head to increase their chances of winning. We also have seen that age has a positive association with the number of head shots absorbed in most weight divisions. For fighters who want to retire as unscathed as they once cut their teeth, it may be wise to get in early and leave the sport as early.

We also see that grappling submission is a highly favored way for fighters on a winning streak to finish their opponents. In weight divisions where the average takedown percentage is high, fighters might thrive by honing their responsive submission skills to cancel out the effectiveness of a takedown. In weight divisions where the average takedown percentage is low, fighters could improve their takedown skills to take advantage of other fighters who are used to standing up and hence, perhaps, less skilled in defending takedowns.

The dataset has far too many descriptive features to find all the meaningful correlations with the response feature through plotting only. We will undertake such a mission in Phase 2 through multiple regression. Should its model fit turn out to be not as promising as we now hope, we shall try NN models to predict post-fight winning streaks of fighters.
